The minimal reproduction shows that the program deliberately aborts with `exit(1)` when it encounters the Markdown pad‑marker `---` at the very start of the input. In the test case the intent was to treat such input as a normal document, but the current source code interprets an early `---` as a fatal error and exits with status 1.

┐ **Root‑cause** – The function that validates the beginning of a Markdown document checks for a leading separator and, on detection, immediately invokes `exit(1)`. This validation is overly strict; a leading separator should be allowed inside a document but only signals a thematic break later on. Consequently, a document that begins with `---` (a legal but unusual opening) causes the program to terminate prematurely, producing the observed failure.

┐ **Minimal local fix** – Allow a leading separator when no preceding content has been seen and proceed to parse the document rather than exiting.

```c
// md2html.c   (around line 45)
if (is_separator(line)) {
    // BEFORE: triggers exit(1) on any leading separator
    // AFTER: just skip the line and continue parsing
    // Continue processing the rest of the input...
}
```

---

#### More thorough root‑cause fix
The current validation conflates the presence of a separator with a syntax error, causing the parser to abort on any leading separator even when it is meant to be part of the content. The proper fix is to:

1. **Detect a leading separator only when there is preceding content** (i.e., it is not the first line), indicating it should start a thematic break.
2. **Treat a leading separator otherwise as ordinary content**, allowing the parser to continue and eventually render the separator as intended.

This may require small changes to the state‑tracking logic so that the parser maintains whether any content has been seen before deciding whether to treat a separator line as an error.

```c
// md2html.c   (more extensive)
bool has_content_seen = false;

for (each line in input) {
    if (is_separator(line) && has_content_seen) {
        // This is a valid thematic break
        // … handle break …
    } else {
        // Normal content or a leading separator – no error
        // … process line as normal …
        has_content_seen = true;
    }
}
```

By adjusting the logic so that a separator at the very start of the document is permitted, the program will no longer exit early and the failing test will pass.

---

### Recommendation
┐ **Fix**: Modify the separator‑detection logic in `md2html.c` to avoid exiting on an early `---` line as shown above. This minimal change removes the erroneous exit while preserving correct handling of thematic breaks later in the document.

